<br>
If you win, you get, nice XP for the 1-2 hours you were in the dungeon. If you have it set to AA XP then your getting more. When I'm set at 100% XP, I get about 40-60% AAXP. I've completed missions in 38 minutes, then used the extra 30 to have fun. I get adventure points, I might get some augments or items, and the big thing for me, I have lots of fun. <br>
<br>
If I lose, and don't die, I get all save the adventure points, though sometimes I get the lower points.<br>
<br>
The only time I don't get those, are when someone pulls out because of an &quot;emergency&quot;, which, is the new &quot;my guild is raiding&quot; excuse. You can't say my guild is raiding in 20 minutes because everyone would jump on you saying, &quot;Then why did you agree to do this if you knew you couldn't commit the whole time?&quot; It's amazing how emergencies have gone up since LDoN. Thankfully, not where I live.<br>
<br>
I've had this happen a few times, but hey, people do shit, so no need to go crazy on them. I do keep track of who these people are, and I will think twice before grouping with them again on one of these. <br>
<br>
The other up side for me? Thoughs that like LDoN and can handle the pace, are becoming better players. They are learning to push thier characters abilities more. The clerics in my guild understand pacifing now, and don't say, well, pacify sucks, so I never use it. Same with enchanters. Now, in a regular dungeon, after we have singled pulled a mob, the enchanter goes and preps the rest of the mobs with pacifies. <br>
<br>
LDoN has made it where I don't want to sit around in one spot pulling and killing the same handful of spawns over and over. It was never my thing to begine with, I get tired of it after 30 minutes, and I've only done it when I was trying to reach a level, or get AA. As a wizard, I was never into solo quadding much either. It gets old faster then grinding. For thems that like it, go for it. <br>
<br>
Most of the people I play with follow the same ideals. They would rather work thier way around a dungeon, then find a spot and spend hours killing the same handful of spawns. LDoN has made them all better players. Better mana management, better understanding of which heals, spells, weapons, aggro manage work. <br>
<br>
Pre LDoN zones and dungeons are easier now. We can move and clear a an area quick and efficently. And then, cause we <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>aren't</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on a timer, relax and med up for the next round.<br>
<br>
